@node "whatis" "What is Spotconv?"

Well this program is something I decided to write after starting to
use the Spot fidonet package.  I would recieve lots of mail that I
wanted to save out, mostly lots of humour files.  Saving each message
out one by one and having to give it a name was quite a task especially
with over 100 messages at time.

I thought why not write a program to split this file.

And so Spotconv was born.

Folders are ascii message saves from Spot program, simply save all the
messages you want as one big file, then set Spotconv on it!

@{" Back To Main Menu " link "main" 0}

@endnode

@node "installation" "Installation"

Stick the Spotconv program file into your c: directory and away you go.

Spotconv can also be utilised by programs such as Directory Opus.
Use the directory opus installation below and then to use simply select 
the appropriate spot file and choose spotconv from the menu.

@{" Back To Main Menu " link "main" 0}

@endnode

@node "opusinstall" "Directory Opus Installation"

1. Load Configuration program
2. Select Menus
3. Choose a menu slot
4. Add an entry as Amigados
5. Enter 'c:spotconv {F}'
   If you want to use options, place them before/after {F}
6. The flags section, select the following
   CD Source
   Output Window
   Run asynchronously
   Workbench to Front
7. Enter an appropriate name for the menu item, such as Spotconv

And away you go!

@{" Back To Main Menu " link "main" 0}

@endnode

@node "cliinstruct" "Cli Instructions"
   
Simple at the prompt type 'Spotconv <foldername> [options]'.

The program will then work away at the folder splitting it into multiple
smaller files labelled 'Spot<no>.doc'. The <no> section of the file name
being a counter.

@{" Back To Main Menu " link "main" 0}

@endnode

@node "options" "Options"

@{b}-r = rename by subject@{ub}
The filenames of the extracted files are named as the subject of that
particular mail.

@{b}-F = include full header@{ub}
Will include the full spot header within the file, this contains information
on the sender, receiver and subject.

@{b}-f = include subject header@{ub}
Will only include the subject header within the file.

@{b}-e = alternate extension, default is '.doc'@{ub}
An alternative extension can be supplied, instead of using the default
'.doc' extension. After the -e add three characters for the extension.
For example, to have .txt extension, use '-etxt'.

@{b}-h = help page@{ub}
Will show this list of options.

@{" Back To Main Menu " link "main" 0}

@endnode

